@database BFP.guide
@node "main" "Specification of map"
Welcome to editor for Benefactor. With this program you will be able to
create whole new levels for the Benefactor.
Each map consists of few elements. Each element belongs to one button
of main panel. This guide is divided basing on these elements.

Creating map is not so hard, but creating icon map is time-consuming,
and other things require manual insertion of numbers.
@{U}Remember@{UU}: Always save map with @{B}.map@{UB} prefix e.g. mymap.map!

@{"Icon Map        " LINK mapa_ikonowa}
@{"General Settings" LINK naglowek}
@{"Water and Sky   " LINK kolory}
@{"Objects         " LINK obiekty}
@{"Triggers        " LINK zdarzenia}
@{"Merrymen        " LINK merrymen}
@endnode

@node "mapa_ikonowa" "Icon Map"
Almost all graphic appearance of level consists of icon map.
On stage of its creation you define shape and look of rooms,
static platforms and so on. Icon map doesn't contain in dynamic
elements, animation.

Keyboard (in map editor window):
@{B}'s'@{UB}   -  Selection of icon
@{B}'t'@{UB}   -  Copy of current icon
@{B}'1'@{UB}   -  Setting the bottom of ladder
@{B}'2'@{UB}   -  Setting the top of ladder
@{B}'3'@{UB}   -  Setting platform

(in icon selection window):
@{B}'c'@{UB}   -  Change of screen

@{"Interactive map" LINK mapa_interaktywna}
@endnode

@node "mapa_interaktywna" "Interactive map"
Additionally some icons can become interactive. For example bottom and top
of ladder, hollow in wall must be signed in special way.
You have to also sign places when hero can jump to higher platform as well
as places when merry-men jump across platforms.

It is possible to connect places on map with triggers.
@endnode

@node "granice_mapy" "Map Boundaries"
Map boundaries are fields that contain in camera vision. In this manner
camera won't move when hero reaches the boundary.
Map boundaries are counted in this way (number in hexadecimal format):

Map width is states in icons.
Left boundary  = Place * $10 + $90
Right boundary = Map width * $10 - $60
@endnode

@node "naglowek" "General settings"
These settings are: width of the map, start position and direction of hero,
starting boundaries, width of mini-map and so on.
Here are general settings:

@{B}BytesPerRow@{UB} - width of map. It's doubled number of icons in row.
(set only on creating of new map).
@{B}StartX, StartY@{UB} - starting coordinates of hero
@{B}Dir@{UB} - direction of hero
@{B}LeftBound@{UB} - left boundary of map
@{B}RightBound@{UB} - right boundary of map
@{B}PixelsPerRow@{UB} -width of mini-map
@{B}Module@{UB} - position in music module

@{"Map boundaries" LINK granice_mapy}
@endnode

@node "kolory" "Water and sky"
The map can contain water level and sky.
Warning: Currently unavailable in editor.
@endnode

@node "obiekty" "Obiekty"
Objects are items, enemies, devices and so on. Each object can
have up to 16 properties. Soon these properties will be described
here.
@endnode

@node "zdarzenia" "Triggers"
Triggers (or events) are needed to setup things like levers and buttons
to work properly. For example event 1 is "pull platform". Now you connect
this event with lever and it's ready.

Each trigger consists of:
@{B}Index@{UB} - number of trigger
@{B}Property@{UB} - property to change. For masked object
it is counted like this: $10 * number of object + $2 * number of property
For non-masked objects you must add $3C0 to this number
@{B}Value 1@{UB} - value 1 of property
@{B}Value 2@{UB} - value 2 of property
@endnode

@node "merrymen", "Merry-men and their routes"
Routes are hardest but with some luck you can manage with it.
Each route node consists of:

Action:
Move (@{B}MOVE@{UB})
Set trigger (@{B}SET@{UB}) - sets given trigger
Wait for trigger (@{B}WAIT@{UB}) - waits for given trigger
Fix (@{B}FIX@{UB}) - fixes damaged device or ladder
Get item (@{B}FILL@{UB}) - gets item from hero
Interact with objects (@{B}DO@{UB}) - interacts with objects on map
Flush inventory (@{B}FLUSH@{UB}) - flushes inventory
Enter gate (@{B}ENTER@{UB}) - enters gate
Teleport (@{B}BEAM@{UB}) - teleports (Techno Treat)
End route (@{B}END@{UB}) - ends route

Here are the rest of settings:
@{B}Target x@{UB} - target coord x
@{B}Target y@{UB} - target coord y
@{B}Action@{UB} - action
@{B}Item@{UB} (optional) - item to pick up
@{B}Trigger@{UB} (optional) - number of trigger
@{B}Value@{UB} (optional) - valu. For SET, WAIT and FIX set it to $FF. For
ENTER and BEAM set it to number of gate/beaming device.
@{B}Node@{UB} (optional) - Offset between this and next node. For FILL
it's offset between this and previous node.
@{B}Face@{UB} - direction at target
@{B}Throw@{UB} - request to fling up
@{B}No return@{UB} - does merryman have to return if blocked way
@{B}Skip Ladders@{UB} - does merryman have to skip ladders
@{B}Push Button@{UB} - does merryman have to push button
@{B}Instant Turn@{UB} - does merryman have to go further after reaching
target icon
@{B}Don't jump over@{UB} - does merryman have to jump over pipes
@endnode
